ious folks by subscribing here:
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Plaid [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/b9cf6100-60b8-4857-bd06-15b3bc9ebe4d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
You may know Plaid [ https://substack.com/redirect/b9cf6100-60b8-4857-bd06-=
15b3bc9ebe4d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] as the company that easily lets you connect and authorize your bank =
to your favorite finance apps.When that original product dropped back in 20=
13, it was like magic and unleashed a whole wave of fintech innovation =E2=
=80=93 think Venmo, Chime, and SoFi. In the decade since, Plaid has establi=
shed itself as one of the leading fintech infrastructure companies and has =
rolled out a whole suite of products that allow businesses to get the most =
out of their financial data - including payments, identity verification, an=
d credit.
The company also has a particularly unique vantage point on the fintech ind=
ustry. It partners with both cutting-edge startups and legacy incumbents, h=
as experienced the ups and downs of the general macro environment over the =
last few years, and, as a financial data network, has an inside view of wha=
t=E2=80=99s working in fintech today.
Each year, the company publishes its Fintech Spotlight Report [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/b9cf6100-60b8-4857-bd06-15b3bc9ebe4d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. This year=E2=80=99s repo=
rt, titled =E2=80=9CA Focus on Profitability [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/b9cf6100-60b8-4857-bd06-15b3bc9ebe4d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=E2=80=9D covers three main topics: improv=
ing profitability, crypto services, and lending. Whether you=E2=80=99re a f=
intech, lender, banker, investor, or just an interested analyst, you=E2=80=
=99ll find valuable insights inside the report, which they are making free =
to download [ https://substack.com/redirect/b9cf6100-60b8-4857-bd06-15b3bc9=
ebe4d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for all Not Boring readers.
Riskophilia
What if we=E2=80=99re thinking about risk backwards?=C2=A0
Over the weekend, a paper in The Journal of Pediatrics titled, Decline in I=
ndependent Activity as a Cause of Decline in Children=E2=80=99s Mental Well=
-being: Summary of the Evidence [ https://substack.com/redirect/eb4c15c4-ab=
f4-453a-95d9-4a6214dcf4c4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] swept the internet.=C2=A0
The authors=E2=80=99 argue that =E2=80=9Ca primary cause of the rise in men=
tal disorders is a decline over decades in opportunities for children and t=
eens to play, roam, and engage in other activities independent of direct ov=
ersight and control by adults.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Right on the first page, they write (emphasis mine):=C2=A0
Over time, however, beginning in the 1960s and accelerating in the 1980s, t=
he implicit understanding shifted from that of children as competent, respo=
nsible, and resilient to the opposite, as advice focused increasingly on ch=
ildren=E2=80=99s needs for supervision and protection. Rutherford noted, as=
 have other reviewers, that in some respects=E2=80=94such as freedom to cho=
ose what they wear or eat=E2=80=94children have gained autonomy over the de=
cades. What has declined specifically is children=E2=80=99s freedom to enga=
ge in activities that involve some degree of risk and personal responsibili=
ty away from adults.
My thesis is that it=E2=80=99s not just the kids.=C2=A0
Replace =E2=80=9Cchildren=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9Cpeople=E2=80=9D and the pa=
ragraph works just as well!=C2=A0
Over the same time period, beginning in the 1960s and accelerating in the 1=
980s, the implicit understanding shifted from that of Americans as competen=
t, responsible, and resilient to the opposite, as advice focused increasing=
ly on Americans=E2=80=99 needs for supervision and protection.
As a quick pulse check, I asked ChatGPT to give me a rough estimate of Amer=
ica=E2=80=99s attitude towards risk every decade since our founding:=C2=A0
This is an admittedly unscientific approach, but I found it interesting. Ch=
atGPT has no horse in this race, and the dropoff from the 1960s to the 1970=
s lines up with the child-raising paper and the rise in regulation. Somethi=
ng changed in the 1970s (cue: wtfhappenedin1971? [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/c1953959-a90c-433b-8521-7b1982c01e25?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]).=C2=A0
If you deconstruct the larger trendline into two =E2=80=93 one from the 177=
0s - 1960s and the other from the 1960s - 2020s =E2=80=93 that change jumps=
 off the page.=C2=A0
We stopped embracing risk and started trying to eliminate it. We went from =
riskophilia to riskophobia.=C2=A0
The 1970s are a fascinating decade for people who think about progress. Tyl=
er Cowen calls the period since 1971 The Great Stagnation [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/64487059-8475-44e7-bdb9-5545c82f9d9c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a half-century slowdown in p=
roductivity and innovation. In WTF Happened in 2023?! [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/b9b47721-9ff9-4677-ba0a-58fe908137b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I wrote that about that year, =
=E2=80=9CYou might have picked up a shift from optimism to pessimism, which=
 trickled into policies, corporate decisions, and then, years later, into t=
he data.=E2=80=9D
We can get more specific here. The 1970s saw the rise of safety culture wit=
h the creation of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC), Environmental Pr=
otection Agency (EPA), and Occupational Safety and Health Administration (O=
HSA), along with the passage of the Clean Air Act, the Occupational Safety =
and Health Act, and the Consumer Product Safety Act.=C2=A0
Inspired by the German environmental movement, which called it =E2=80=9CVor=
sorgeprinzip,=E2=80=9D or foresight principle, the 1970s also birthed the p=
recautionary principle. In simple terms, it means =E2=80=9Cbetter safe than=
 sorry.=E2=80=9D In less simple terms, the precautionary principle suggests=
 that if an action or policy has the potential to cause harm, in the absenc=
e of scientific consensus, the burden of proof falls on those advocating fo=
r the action or policy, not those opposing it.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s guilty until proven innocent for new things, but worse, becaus=
e it forestalls the opportunity for a trial in the first place.=C2=A0
The basic problem with the precautionary principle is that, in its strong f=
orm, it=E2=80=99s like running a cost-benefit analysis without the benefit =
column. A single =E2=80=9CX=E2=80=9D in the cost column is enough to genera=
te a =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D decision.=C2=A0
More bluntly, it doesn=E2=80=99t work. In a 2005 paper, The Precautionary P=
rinciple as a Basis for Decision Making [ https://substack.com/redirect/84a=
3cd22-afa3-495c-becc-450090b5a966?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Harvard legal scholar Cass Sunstein argues =E2=
=80=9Cthat the precautionary principle does not help individuals or nations=
 make difficult choices in a non-arbitrary way. Taken seriously, it can be =
paralyzing, providing no direction at all.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Worse, attempting to eliminate legible risks just creates new ones. =E2=80=
=9CIt turns out,=E2=80=9D he writes, =E2=80=9Cthat the danger that regulati=
on will create new or different risk profiles is the rule, not the exceptio=
n.=E2=80=9D
The canonical example here is nuclear energy. The NRC literally uses a prin=
ciple that demands that radiation be =E2=80=9CAs Low As Reasonably Achievab=
le,=E2=80=9D an asymptotically impossible goal. Make it safer, then safer, =
then safer, until you don=E2=80=99t make it at all. Regulation has contribu=
ted to making nuclear so expensive that we effectively don=E2=80=99t build =
it. By minimizing the 0.03 deaths per terawatt hour of electricity produced=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/479f203d-36bf-4385-a434-d6c911d38b62?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], we increas=
e the risk of deaths from other fuel sources, the impacts of climate change=
, and dependence on foreign energy. And we forestall an energy abundant fut=
ure and its untold benefits. We lower the ceiling, and the floor.=C2=A0
We trade freedom not for safety, but for the illusion of safety.=C2=A0
Illusion, because: you can=E2=80=99t eliminate risk.=C2=A0
Whether we=E2=80=99re talking about parenting or regulation, the idea that =
you can is comforting. It provides a sense of control. Everyone wants their=
 kids to be safe. But risks don=E2=80=99t operate in a vacuum. By trying to=
 limit known but potentially small risks, you open yourself up to bigger bu=
t less legible risks elsewhere.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s like squeezing a water balloon. Push on one side, the water mo=
ves to the other. Push too hard, and the balloon explodes.=C2=A0
Embracing risk can make you antifragile by building resilience and adaptabi=
lity; running from it can make you fragile by removing opportunities to bui=
ld the same.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s what the parenting paper argues, and I argue that the same t=
hing is true for adults, companies, and even nations.=C2=A0
When World War II struck, America sprung to action, transforming itself int=
o the factory that won the war. Today, as Noah Smith writes [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/f1bac768-633f-4eb7-873a-43e669242265?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re not=
 ready for the big one.=E2=80=9D Our shell-making capacity is about 3% what=
 it was thirty years ago, and China has a 200:1 shipbuilding advantage over=
 the US.=C2=A0
I hope to god we avoid World War III, but the fact that it=E2=80=99s even o=
n the table =E2=80=93 that war is happening around the world as we speak =
=E2=80=93 should serve as a wake-up call that the world is full of risk, an=
d that by trying to avoid it, we allow it to bloom.
There were a million different reasons that 1971 was a turning point from g=
rowth to stagnation: oil shocks, the shift from manufacturing to services, =
declining energy usage, the abandonment of the gold standard, increased reg=
ulation. But I think it runs deeper than that, to the cultural core of the =
country, which is why the same pattern shows up in the economy and in the w=
ay parents raise their kids.=C2=A0
The shift from optimism to pessimism, from growth to degrowth, from hope to=
 doom, and from riskophilia to riskophobia was the result of a cultural mov=
ement, and we need a cultural movement in the other direction to get our sw=
agger back.=C2=A0
That might seem naive. There are those who believe that our decline is a fa=
it accompli. I=E2=80=99m not one of those people. It=E2=80=99s why I have b=
een banging the drum on optimism and telling the stories of the people and =
companies that do embrace risk to try to fix the biggest problems they can =
tackle. A movement got us into this mess, and a movement can get us out of =
it.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve been wanting to write a piece [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
64a1197f-d255-4cab-a341-481d9a347a4c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] on America=E2=80=99s attitude towards risk f=
or a while. The good news is, the tide seems to be shifting already.=C2=A0
A couple of weeks ago, the All-In podcast=E2=80=99s David Friedberg, who=E2=
=80=99s had to fight through the precautionary principle as an entrepreneur=
, went in on the =E2=80=9Ctotal lack of assumption of risk generally in the=
 US which limits progress in meaningful ways=E2=80=9D:
Watch it.=C2=A0
And yesterday, a16z co-founder Marc Andreessen wrote The Techno-Optimist Ma=
nifesto [ https://substack.com/redirect/675409de-3e0d-4320-9387-c1b8350ec69=
3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], off=
ering an aggressively optimistic perspective and going to town on the preca=
utionary principle:=C2=A0
Our enemy is the Precautionary Principle, which would have prevented virtua=
lly all progress since man first harnessed fire. The Precautionary Principl=
e was invented to prevent the large-scale deployment of civilian nuclear po=
wer, perhaps the most catastrophic mistake in Western society in my lifetim=
e. The Precautionary Principle continues to inflict enormous unnecessary su=
ffering on our world today. It is deeply immoral, and we must jettison it w=
ith extreme prejudice.
Read the whole thing if you haven=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t need to re-litigate the points Friedberg and Marc made. I a=
gree with them. And if they sound a bit extreme, it=E2=80=99s because movem=
ents aren=E2=80=99t started by tepidly considering every point and counterp=
oint. The culture shifts through a great Overton Window tug-of-war.=C2=A0
If the precautionary principle that has underpinned the last half-century o=
f riskophoboa in America has pushed safety by erasing the benefits column, =
then the appropriate counterbalance is to make a case for erasing the cost =
column.=C2=A0
If that case lands, we=E2=80=99ll pull hard enough that we end up somewhere=
 in the middle, taking Cass Sunstein=E2=80=99s recommendation that we throw=
 out the precautionary principle in favor of a radical new framework: cost-=
benefit analysis.=C2=A0
Kids should ride bikes with their friends, but they should wear a helmet. T=
hey should roam freely, but they shouldn=E2=80=99t go to bars. We should em=
brace nuclear energy, but we should build containment domes. We should prot=
ect the environment, but we shouldn=E2=80=99t let every bobwhite quail egg =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/34a5ec9a-0cda-4227-808f-1ced2dd26cdc?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] stand in the=
 way of a better future for humans. Every decision has costs, and benefits.=
=C2=A0
The movement underfoot isn=E2=80=99t against each other or against the gove=
rnment. America has worked best when its government and people were pulling=
 in the same direction: forward.=C2=A0
The movement is against the idea of risk minimization as a goal. It=E2=80=
=99s against the culture of safetyism [ https://substack.com/redirect/042c8=
ddd-6d24-4a24-b09c-b55dc59c3859?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that we=E2=80=99ve all allowed to seep into every=
 corner of our lives. It=E2=80=99s for the more vibrant, alive, and vigorou=
s world we can build when we embrace risk with eyes wide open.=C2=A0
This movement is about much more than tech. The parenting paper helped me r=
ealize that the issue runs deeper, and that the solutions must too. From ou=
r homes to our startups to our government, we need to take responsibility f=
or our actions and outcomes.=C2=A0
I have good news and bad news: we are not children.=C2=A0
There is no parent to protect us, and even if there were, it might do more =
harm than good. So drop the illusion. Embrace risk. Roam free. Live vigorou=
sly.=C2=A0
The reason we=E2=80=99ve made so much progress over the past half-century d=
espite our decelerating risk appetite is that a brave few have chosen to ta=
ke risk on and win. I write about the entrepreneurs among them, but they=E2=
=80=99re everywhere. Someone probably pops to mind for you.=C2=A0
Imagine what the world could be if more of us joined them. We are competent=
, responsible, and resilient. We have the freedom to engage in activities t=
hat involve some degree of risk and personal responsibility. Embrace it. Jo=
in the movement.=C2=A0
My hunch is that the government will follow. They=E2=80=99re just been givi=
ng us the sense of protection we=E2=80=99ve demanded. Let=E2=80=99s demand =
something better. Vox populi, vox Dei.=C2=A0
I refuse to believe that America=E2=80=99s best days are behind it. Decline=
 is not inevitable. But it takes more than tech. It=E2=80=99s up to all of =
us to cut through the cruft, get back to the sense of freedom and adventure=
 that make the country great, and build from there.=C2=A0
Go do that risky thing you=E2=80=99ve been putting off. Now. Build the musc=
le. Spread the word: we=E2=80=99re going risk-on.=20
The only way out is up, even if it=E2=80=99s a little risky up there.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/37225a1e-9f87-4bbe-b194-45d48=
5b1ac28?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox with the =
Weekly Dose on Friday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

