ically impossible goal. Make it safer, then safer, then safer, until you do=
n&#8217;t make it at all. Regulation has contributed to making nuclear so e=
xpensive that we effectively don&#8217;t build it. By minimizing the </span=
><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/479f203d-36bf-4385-a434-d6c911d38=
b62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=
 style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">0.03 deaths =
per terawatt hour of electricity produced</a><span>, we increase the risk o=
f deaths from other fuel sources, the impacts of climate change, and depend=
ence on foreign energy. And we forestall an energy abundant future and its =
untold benefits. We lower the ceiling, and the floor.&#160;</span></p><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;"><span>We trade freedom not for safety, but for the </span><em>=
illusion</em><span> of safety.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 6=
4, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Illusion, =
because: you can&#8217;t eliminate risk.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64=
, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Whether=
 we&#8217;re talking about parenting or regulation, the idea that you can i=
s comforting. It provides a sense of control. Everyone wants their kids to =
be safe. But risks don&#8217;t operate in a vacuum. By trying to limit know=
n but potentially small risks, you open yourself up to bigger but less legi=
ble risks elsewhere.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It&#8217;s like squeezing a=
 water balloon. Push on one side, the water moves to the other. Push too ha=
rd, and the balloon explodes.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-contai=
ner-static" style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;=
"><figure style=3D"margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;"><table class=3D"image-wrap=
