ore dramatic than I was going for, but you get it; giphy</em></figcaption><=
/figure></div><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Embracing risk can make you antifragile by =
building resilience and adaptability; running from it can make you fragile =
by removing opportunities to build the same.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rg=
b(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Tha=
t&#8217;s what the parenting paper argues, and I argue that the same thing =
is true for adults, companies, and even nations.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
><span>When World War II struck, America sprung to action, transforming its=
elf into the factory that won the war. Today, as Noah Smith </span><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/f1bac768-633f-4eb7-873a-43e669242265?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">writes</a><span>, =
&#8220;We&#8217;re not ready for the big one.&#8221; Our shell-making capac=
ity is about 3% what it was thirty years ago, and China has a 200:1 shipbui=
lding advantage over the US.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64,=
 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I hope to go=
d we avoid World War III, but the fact that it&#8217;s even on the table &#=
8211; that war is happening around the world as we speak &#8211; should ser=
ve as a wake-up call that the world is full of risk, and that by trying to =
avoid it, we allow it to bloom.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There were a million d=
ifferent reasons that 1971 was a turning point from growth to stagnation: o=
il shocks, the shift from manufacturing to services, declining energy usage=
, the abandonment of the gold standard, increased regulation. But I think i=
t runs deeper than that, to the cultural core of the country, which is why =
the same pattern shows up in the economy and in the way parents raise their=
 kids.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The shift from optimism to pessimism, fro=
m growth to degrowth, from hope to doom, and from riskophilia to riskophobi=
a was the result of a cultural movement, and we need a cultural movement in=
 the other direction to get our swagger back.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Th=
at might seem naive. There are those who believe that our decline is a fait=
 accompli. I&#8217;m not one of those people. It&#8217;s why I have been ba=
nging the drum on optimism and telling the stories of the people and compan=
ies that do embrace risk to try to fix the biggest problems they can tackle=
=2E A movement got us into this mess, a=
nd a movement can get us out of it.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>I&#8217;ve been </span><a href=3D"https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/64a1197f-d255-4cab-a341-481d9a347a4c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(6=
4, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">wanting to write a piece</a><span>=
 on America&#8217;s attitude towards risk for a while. The good news is, th=
e tide seems to be shifting already.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">A co=
uple of weeks ago, the All-In podcast&#8217;s David Friedberg, who&#8217;s =
had to fight through the precautionary principle as an entrepreneur, went i=
n on the &#8220;total lack of assumption of risk generally in the US which =
limits progress in meaningful ways&#8221;:</p><a href=3D"https://substack.c=
om/redirect/eef09c34-8360-4fc6-979c-4910fdebc5d6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"youtub=
e-wrap" data-component-name=3D"Youtube2ToDOMStatic" style=3D"display: block=
; margin: 1.6em 0;"><img src=3D"https://substackcdn.com/image/youtube/w_550=
,c_limit/l_youtube_play_qyqt8q,w_120/UZtQcnt12SM" style=3D"-ms-interpolatio=
n-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; mar=
gin: 0 auto; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; width: 100%;"></a><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">Watch it.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>And yesterday, a1=
6z co-founder Marc Andreessen wrote </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.=
com/redirect/675409de-3e0d-4320-9387-c1b8350ec693?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); text-decoration: underline;">The Techno-Optimist Manifesto</a><span>,<=
/span></em><span> offering an aggressively optimistic perspective</span><em=
> </em><span>and going to town on the precautionary principle:&#160;</span>=
</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; pa=
dding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>Our enemy is the Precau=
tionary Principle, which would have prevented virtually all progress since =
man first harnessed fire. The Precautionary Principle was invented to preve=
nt the large-scale deployment of civilian nuclear power, perhaps the most c=
atastrophic mistake in Western society in my lifetime. The Precautionary Pr=
inciple continues to inflict enormous unnecessary suffering on our world to=
day. It is </em><span>deeply</span><em> immoral, and we must jettison it wi=
th extreme prejudice.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 6=
4); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Read the whole=
 thing if you haven&#8217;t.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I don&#8217;t need =
to re-litigate the points Friedberg and Marc made. I agree with them. And i=
f they sound a bit extreme, it&#8217;s because movements aren&#8217;t start=
ed by tepidly considering every point and counterpoint. The culture shifts =
through a great Overton Window tug-of-war.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If th=
e precautionary principle that has underpinned the last half-century of ris=
kophoboa in America has pushed safety by erasing the benefits column, then =
the appropriate counterbalance is to make a case for erasing the cost colum=
n.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If that case lands, we&#8217;ll pull hard eno=
ugh that we end up somewhere in the middle, taking Cass Sunstein&#8217;s re=
commendation that we throw out the precautionary principle in favor of a ra=
dical new framework: cost-benefit analysis.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>Kids should ride bikes with their friends, but they should wear a helmet.=
 They should roam freely, but they shouldn&#8217;t go to bars. We should em=
brace nuclear energy, but we should build containment domes. We should prot=
ect the environment, but we shouldn&#8217;t let every </span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/34a5ec9a-0cda-4227-808f-1ced2dd26cdc?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color=
: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">bobwhite quail egg</a><span=
> stand in the way of a better future for humans. Every decision has costs,=
 and benefits.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The movement underfoot isn=
&#8217;t against each other or against the government. America has worked b=
est when its government and people were pulling in the same direction: forw=
ard.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The movement is against the idea of r=
isk minimization as a goal. It&#8217;s </span><a href=3D"https://substack.c=
om/redirect/042c8ddd-6d24-4a24-b09c-b55dc59c3859?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 6=
4); text-decoration: underline;">against the culture of safetyism</a><span>=
 that we&#8217;ve all allowed to seep into every corner of our lives. It&#8=
217;s </span><em>for </em><span>the more vibrant, alive, and vigorous world=
 we can build when we embrace risk with eyes wide open.&#160;</span></p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">This movement is about much more than tech. The parenting pa=
per helped me realize that the issue runs deeper, and that the solutions mu=
st too. From our homes to our startups to our government, we need to take r=
esponsibility for our actions and outcomes.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I ha=
ve good news and bad news: we are not children.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
There is no parent to protect us, and even if there were, it might do more =
harm than good. So drop the illusion. Embrace risk. Roam free. Live vigorou=
sly.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The reason we&#8217;ve made so much progres=
s over the past half-century despite our decelerating risk appetite is that=
 a brave few have chosen to take risk on and win. I write about the entrepr=
eneurs among them, but they&#8217;re everywhere. Someone probably pops to m=
ind for you.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Imagine what the world could be if =
more of us joined them. We are competent, responsible, and resilient. We ha=
ve the freedom to engage in activities that involve some degree of risk and=
 personal responsibility. Embrace it. Join the movement.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">My hunch is that the government will follow. They&#8217;re just b=
een giving us the sense of protection we&#8217;ve demanded. Let&#8217;s dem=
and something better. Vox populi, vox Dei.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I ref=
use to believe that America&#8217;s best days are behind it. Decline is not=
 inevitable. But it takes more than tech. It&#8217;s up to all of us to cut=
 through the cruft, get back to the sense of freedom and adventure that mak=
e the country great, and build from there.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Go do=
 that risky thing you&#8217;ve been putting off. Now. Build the muscle. Spr=
ead the word: we&#8217;re going risk-on. </p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64,=
 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The only way=
 out is up, even if it&#8217;s a little risky up there.</p><div style=3D"fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;"><hr style=3D"background: #e0e0e0; border=
: none; height: 1px; margin: 32px 0; padding: 0;"></div><p style=3D"color: =
